organizations under large uncertainty an analysis of the fukushima catastrophe siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display organizations under large uncertainty an analysis of the fukushima catastrophe type siepr discussion paper 11 001 author s masahiko aoki geoffrey rothwell published 10 15 11 abstract this paper analyzes the impacts of the march 11 2011 earthquake and tsunami at the fukushima nuclear power plant in japan which were amplified by a failure of coordination across the plant corporate industrial and regulatory levels resulting in a nuclear catastrophe comparable in cost to chernobyl it derives generic lessons for industrial structure and regulatory frame for the electric power industry by identifying the two shortcomings of a horizontal coordination mechanism instability under large shocks and the lack of defense in depth the suggested policy response is to harness the power of open interface rule based modularity by creating an independent nuclear safety commission and an independent system operator owning the transmission grid module in japan we propose a transitory price mechanism that can restrain price volatility while providing investment incentives full text full text stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
